h3. Issue Summary
Configuring an Agile Wallboard Gadget using any boards and any quick filters doesn't apply the filters to the gadget result. 

The behaviour is not reproducible on the project board.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create board;
 # Create some quick filters;
 # Add the Agile Wallboard Gadget on a Dashboard;
 # Configure it with the board and the quick filter you'd like to use;
 # Try changing the quick filter on the Agile Wallboard gadget and refresh the gadget/page;

h3. Expected Results
The issues are updated on the gadget;

h3. Actual Results
The issues are still the same;

For example:
Quick filter configuration: 
 !image-2020-10-08-11-48-47-126.png|thumbnail! 

Agile Wallboard Results when selecting "Open issues" filter:

 !image-2020-10-08-11-49-02-868.png|thumbnail! 

Agile Wallboard Results when selecting "Closed Issues" quick filter:

 !image-2020-10-08-11-49-21-039.png|thumbnail! 

Even by refreshing both browser page and gadget, it didn't refresh.


h3. Workaround

 Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h4. Feature Request

Would like to request for a feature where administrators would have access to restricts groups to show up under share filters and share dashboard option .

Basically, the user would like to request for a feature where they would have access to restrict to show groups which are configured for application access. Which means that Jira should show all groups of the user where the user is member of it except global groups which are configured for application access
h4. Workaround

Add this to your announcement banner
{code:java}
<script type='text/javascript'>
//Workaround for JRASERVER-71670
AJS.$(function() {  

    function killNodes() {
        //Add Groups to remove here
        AJS.$("select[name='groupName'] option[value='jira-software-users']").remove();

    }

    var urlPath = AJS.$(location).attr('pathname');
    if (urlPath.toLowerCase().indexOf("editsubscription") >= 0 || urlPath.toLowerCase().indexOf("viewsubscriptions")  >= 0) {
        killNodes();
    }

    const targetNode = document.getElementById('jira'); //body element
    const config = { attributes: false, childList: true, subtree: true };
    const callback = function(mutationsList, observer) {
        // Use traditional 'for loops' for IE 11
        for(const mutation of mutationsList) {
            if (mutation.type === 'childList') {
                killNodes();
            }
        }
    };

    const observer = new MutationObserver(callback);
    observer.observe(targetNode, config);
});

</script>

{code}

(i) Important notes on workaround
* If you have more groups than just jira-software-users that you wish to block, then please duplicate the line and change the group name as desired: {code}AJS.$("select[name='groupName'] option[value='jira-software-users']").remove();{code}
* This fix was tested on Jira 8.5.6, and is not guaranteed to work on other version of Jira. Having said that, unless there is a major change to this feature, it will probably work.

At the moment the official documentation about sharing filters https://confluence.atlassian.com/jiracoreserver/saving-your-search-as-a-filter-939937724.html states that:

{quote}
Filters that you have created or have permission to edit can be shared with other users, user groups, projects, and project roles. They can also be shared globally. You can choose whether you want to share the filter with the permission to edit, or only to view. Any filter that is shared is visible to users who have the 'Jira Administrators' global permission
{quote}

However while it is possible to share a filter with a group, any logged in user, every user in the roles of a project, or to any specific role within a project, it is not possible to share a filter with a single specific user.

Please correct the documentation about it.

h3. Issue Summary
The Site Title font size is incorrect and too big after upgrading to Jira 8.12.0

This may be due to AUI 9 changes shipped in this version

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Jira Admin -> System -> Look and Feel
 # Enable Show Site Tite

h3. Expected Results
The Site Title matches the theme
 !screenshot-1.png|thumbnail! 

h3. Actual Results
The font size, colour, and hoverover link of the Site Title are bad
 !screenshot-3.png|thumbnail! 

h3. Workaround
[Configure your announcement banner|https://confluence.atlassian.com/adminjiraserver/configuring-an-announcement-banner-938846985.html] to include this
{code}
<style>
.aui-header .aui-header-logo .aui-header-logo-text {
    display: block;
    float: left;
    font-size: 14px;
    line-height: 1.4286;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 10px 0 10px 10px;
}.aui-header-logo-text {
    color: #deebff;
    font-weight: 500;
    text-transform: none;
    letter-spacing: -.01em;
}
</style> 
{code}

{color:#172b4d}“Access keys are used in the application in order to be able to call up functions efficiently. Some problems arise in connection with access keys:{color}
{color:#172b4d} ▪ The application has its own system for keyboard operation (see figure). Access keys are called up without a control key, which causes the problem for blind users that not all access keys can be activated immediately because the screen reader does not pass the activated keys on to the browser, but uses them for its own control. Screen reader users must instruct the screen reader to allow certain commands through. This is done again using a key combination. For the JAWS screen reader, this is the key combination INSERT + 3. This means that two key combinations must be activated in order to trigger an action. It's not efficient.{color}
{color:#172b4d} ▪ Some functions are structurally marked with the accesskey attribute. These are then output by the screen reader together with the browser's own control button. For Chrome, this is the ALT key. In this way, for example, the combination ALT + D is output as an access key for the main navigation point “Dashboards”. However, this does not correspond to the application's own operation and it also sets the focus on the address line of the browser. Blind users cannot use this access key.{color}
{color:#172b4d} ▪ A complicating factor is that the use of access keys is elementary for blind users, since the main navigation cannot be operated by screen reader users.{color}
{color:#172b4d} ▪ The initial shortcut "?" For opening the accesskey definition must be known to the user, otherwise it cannot be reached because the shortcuts cannot be displayed via the main navigation. In addition, this access key does not work easily when the screen reader is switched on{color}

{color:#172b4d}Graphics cannot be perceived by blind users and cannot be interpreted by screen readers. Instead, screen readers output alternative texts that were specified for the image. The following problems arise in this context:{color}
{color:#172b4d} On some pages, the screen reader does not output alternative texts for some images because they are not marked with the alt attribute, for example the first icons of the sprint issues in the backlog or the same icons in the active sprint. With these elements, the alternative text is implemented on the surrounding elements and is not output by the screen reader. (see picture1){color}
{color:#172b4d}  {color}
